flowRoot.flowPara: An age-lifespan diagram separates the members of a birth cohort by their eventual completed lifespans. Births are spread out on the left axis according to the cohort's eventual lifetable death distribution, which is unknown at birth. Lifelines descend downward and to the right until death on the bottom axis. This diagram allows us to separate years lived and years left over the lifecourse for individuals of varying lifespan. Panel studies such as HRS, with detailed interview dates, birth dates, and follow-up death dates, permit use of this perspective. For the 1915-1919 birth cohort, we can fill in patterns in the little green area marked below.

flowRoot.flowPara: We aim to determine the extent to which variables commonly used to describe health, wellbeing, and disability in old-age vary primarily as a function of years lived (chronological age), years left (thanatological age), or as a function of both. We analyze data from the US Health and Retirement Study (HRS) to estimate chronological age and time-to-death patterns in 78 such variables. We describe results from the birth cohort born 1915-1919 in the final 12 years of life. Our results show that most markers used to study well-being in old-age vary along both the chronological and thanatological age dimensions, but some markers are exclusively a function of one dimension only, and others display different patterns between the sexes.

IThe HRS covers 20 years of observations (1992-2011). The 1915-1919 cohort entered observation in ages 72-76, and had reached a maximum of age 95 by 2011. In the area marked in green, we have 8137 observations of 1919 individuals from this cohort that have died since the first interview. The green area contains enough information to allow measurement within the final 12 years of life. Patterns are loess-smoothed, also borrowing information from adjacent birth cohorts.
Thanatological age is synonymous in the literature with time-to-death, remaining years of life, and years left.
These lines run horizontal in the diagram.
To be born at thanatological age 80 implies eventually dying at chronological age 80, with a completed lifespan of 80.

Most demography is well grounded in chronological age, but exclusive reliance on chronological age patterns to understand how the ageing process works is imprecise. Some life transitions, states, and changes in state intensities are almost exclusively a function of time to death. There are some instances where chronological age captures almost all pertinent variation, but this appears to be more an exception than a rule. In cases where a characteristic strongly varies as a function of time to death, the common practice of aggregation over chronological age may misrepresent time trends and misguide analyses about change over time and expectations for the future. Measurement of the end-of-life trajectories of characteristics is useful in such cases as a way of separating mortality patterns from patterns in characteristics themselves.
As an example of a misleading result, look at the probability of ever having had psychological problems among males, 1915-1919 birth cohort.

It might seem reasonable to conclude from this plot that the probability of ever having had psych. problems increases with age, which can (mis)lead to other kinds of conclusions about the consequences of population ageing. In this paper, we use full information on end-of-life trajectories to demonstrate a better way to think about such patterns. We return to this specific case in the surface plots to the right, but first examine the large diagram.
95% confidence bands from loess fit

You can think of this big triangle as sitting atop a diagonal cohort line from a standard Lexis diagram (orthogonally). If you do this to each cohort line in a Lexis doagram, you get a sort of prism. Tim is currently working on the idea of said age-time space. If you think that's cool, then check out the idea stub under this link (paper in very early stages)

The contour lines in this surface are mostly horizontal, which means that psychological problems varied primarily as a function of time to death among US males born 1915-1919. An interaction with the survival curve of this cohort produces the spurious pattern shown in the lower left corner of this poster. Many characteristics display this kind of pattern.

Vertical contour lines indicate characteristics that vary by chronological age. Back pain is an example of a characteristic that varies vary almost exlusively as a function of chronological age, at least for this cohort in the section of lifespans captured here. Other characteristics like this include current smoking, arthritis, and self reports of current versus former memory.

A few characteristics vary neither by chronological nor by thanatological age, but rather by the sum of these two dimensions. Characteristcs that vary by lifespan can be thought to determine or correlate with ultimate lifespan. Other such characterics include lung disease (males), frequency of dental visits (both sexes), and diabetes (females).

Contour lines that run perpendicular to lifelines indicate that the intensity of a given characteristic increasesboth with the approach to death and with chronological age. Most of the 78 variables we explore fall either in this or the thanatological category (or somewhere in between). Males from this cohort display nearly 45° contour lines for the probability of ever having been diagnosed with high blood pressure.

All 78 of the indicators we tested are commonly used to describe population ageing, and very few of them are exclusively a function of chronological age. If this finding is sustained in other cohorts and populations, and if other indicators here untested also display similar temporal complexity, we submit that the common discourse and debate on the nature and impacts of population ageing ought to be better informed by more judicious measurement and description in terms of thanatological and chronological age. We hope that this perspective helps researchers to frame how characteristics associated with ageing vary over age and time, and to qualify the likely future impact of population ageing. We also hope that the diagram explored here finds other uses.
